Citizens line up for nucleic acid test at a testing site in Changchun, northeast China's Jilin Province, March 20, 2022. Photo:Xinhua  A citizen of Changchun, Northeast China's Jilin Province, was arrested by Changchun police for fabricating and spreading false information involving the COVID-19 epidemic on the internet.The Kuancheng district branch of Changchun Public Security Bureau busted a case of spreading false information on the internet on Wednesday and took criminal coercive measures against the suspect surnamed Zhen.According to the announcement, Zhen maliciously fabricated and released false information via WeChat in a group chat of more than 100 people. He claimed that all the staffers of a certain neighborhood were infected by COVID-19, and infected residents were left unattended to and some even committed suicide. The false information spread quickly and widely, causing a serious negative impact on the community, the announcement said.On Wednesday, Zhen confessed his crime to the police. Zhen was then taken into criminal coercive measures in accordance with the law for fabricating and intentionally spreading false information. The case is currently under further investigation.In its announcement, the Changchun public security authorities emphasized that citizens' posts on the internet must not exceed the legal bottom line, otherwise they have to bear the consequences.Jilin is one of the most affected provinces in China's latest wave of the COVID-19 outbreak, where some residents had reported shortages of food such as vegetables and eggs amid the prolonged lockdown management. On Wednesday, Changchun reported 997 confirmed domestically transmitted cases and 422 asymptomatic infections.https://www.globaltimes.cn/page/202203/1257204.shtml Global Times